# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: grand-final
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The **1878 VFA season** was the second season of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), the highest-level Australian rules football competition in the colony of Victoria.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Like the 1877 season, the existence of the VFA was effectively an administrative change only, and there was no significant change to the manner in which matches were scheduled and played – or the premiership decided – compared to the unaffiliated 1876 season.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The premiership was won by the Geelong Football Club, after it defeated Melbourne in a playoff match on 5 October.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] It was the club's first VFA premiership, and the first in a sequence of three consecutive premierships won from 1878 to 1880.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The number of senior metropolitan clubs in the Association increased from five to seven in 1878, with Essendon and West Melbourne being newly promoted to senior ranks for 1878, having been leading junior teams in 1877.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Additionally, several provincial teams, including premiers Geelong, competed as senior clubs affiliated with the Association.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Among the metropolitan clubs, Melbourne had the best record, finishing with eleven wins and five draws from its twenty-three matches, ahead of Carlton, whose record was seventeen wins and one draw from twenty-four matches.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Despite Carlton having a superior record, at the time, Melbourne and Carlton were considered to be by far the strongest of the metropolitan clubs, with Melbourne's position as the top club based almost entirely on the head-to-head matches between the two clubs, of which Melbourne won all four.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Among the provincial clubs, Geelong was by far the strongest, having gone through the season undefeated with fifteen wins and one draw from sixteen matches.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] However, Geelong had played only three games against metropolitan clubs (wins against West Melbourne, Carlton and Hotham), while its provincial opponents were not considered as strong as the metropolitan competition.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] To resolve the matter of the premiership, Melbourne and Geelong scheduled a premiership play-off match — the first in Association history — for 5 October, the week after the season was to have finished, at the MCG.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] Geelong won the play-off match by four goals to win the premiership.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The below table details the playing records of the seven senior metropolitan clubs and Geelong in all matches during the 1878 season.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The clubs are listed in the order in which they were ranked in *The Australasian*.
[src:grand-final/1878-vfa-season] The senior records include the premiership playoff match.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The **1889 SAFA Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Norwood and Port Adelaide, held at the Adelaide Oval on the 5 October 1889.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The match is recognised as "the first-ever grand final in Australian football".
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The game resulted in a victory for Norwood, who beat Port Adelaide by two goals, marking the club's ninth premiership and third in a row.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Norwood's captain, Alfred Waldron, was considered the best player on the ground by field umpire John Trait.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The match was attended by an estimated 11,000 people.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The match was required after Port Adelaide and Norwood had ended with an identical win–loss–draw record at the conclusion of the regular 1889 SAFA season.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Port Adelaide's two losses both were at the hands of Norwood.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Meanwhile, Norwood's losses were one game to Port Adelaide and another to Adelaide.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] In Round 14, both clubs played the only draw of the 1889 SAFA season.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] As such, this match between Norwood and Port Adelaide was the first-ever fixture in the SAFA's history to decide the premiership.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Victoria's top Australian rules football umpires John Trait was employed for the special match.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] In Melbourne media he was referred to as the "Prince of Umpires".
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] When Trait took to the field he was greeted by a loud cheer.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The match was considered the best of the season in South Australia and partial credit was given to John Trait's umpiring helping facilitate the spectacle.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] James Shaw, the mayor of Adelaide at the time, complimented Trait after the match for his umpiring.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] After the game William Bushby approached Trait and said that himself and "all his team were quite satisfied" with the umpires decisions.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The state government put on additional trains on the Port Adelaide line in anticipation for the large attendance for the match.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] A large amount of money was bet on the game compared to normal for football matches in Adelaide at the time.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Overall Port Adelaide were favourites with punters early, especially with smaller bets.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] However, by the time the game started Norwood had been backed into favouritism as a result of some late large stakes.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Extra police were deployed for the match, and post-game reports suggest that there was little incident apart from the need to clear the switchback railway of people trying to garner a vantage point of the match.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Police were required to clear people from climbing Adelaide Oval's switchback rollercoaster, as many in the large crowd were seeking prime vantage points to watch the match.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Norwood won the toss and elected to kick with the wind towards the Riverbank end.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] As a result of Norwood winning the toss, Port Adelaide's John McKenzie started the match and kicked north towards the scoreboard end.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Straight away both teams played at a frantic pace.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Following an even contest for the ball in front of the members' pavilion, Port Adelaide player Rudolph Ewers was thrown on the boundary-line.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] As a result, umpire Trait paid him a free.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Ewers used this free to kick forward to George Davis, who himself would receive another free for a breach, and Hamilton obtaining from Davis with a beautiful kicked the first Grand Final's first goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] After scoring the first goal, the Port Adelaide players settled to work quickly.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The dash of Port players had somewhat surprised Norwood, but they replied with an equally strong rush.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Port Adelaide defender Tomlin for a moment averted the danger posed by the Norwood's rush, but Charlie Woods, who was following, aided by Daly, landed the leather right forward, where it went out.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] At the resulting throw in Charlie Woods was held and was awarded a free which he used to kick a goal and equalize the scores.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Rudolph Ewers of the Ports started the next play and beat his opponent Oswald Bertram forcing the Norwoods to quickly defend.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] A little mark gave Harry Phillips a chance but the often reliable player missed.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Waldron and Rawson transferred to the centre, where Daly and McGrath sent it forward, bat Dempster was in the way, and the Ports with a fast rush stormed the Norwoods' citadel.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Charlie Fry passed to Davis, and again the red flag went up.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Both teams were making tremendous effort, and the football shown was of the highest quality.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Norwoods, who were reserving some of their men, had Roberts and McGrath off following, Woods and Wilson taking their places.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Off again, Norwood with a quick, concerted movement, placed the Ports on the defensive.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Roberts tried a long shot, but the ball only landed in front.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Woods marked a good distance off, and with unerring aim sent the sphere clean through the centre.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Again the eastern team, who were showing splendid, clean football, prevailed, Shaw being responsible for the sphere going forward.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Nothing disheartened, the Norwoods returned to the attack, Charlie Woods sending it forward, and then Lowe made a mistake: The ball came up to goal, and instead of kicking with the wind, he turned round and dispatched across.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The ball was rolling past the goal when Dixon making a desperate effort touched it with his foot, and it went through within six inches of the post.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The play was next taken to the Ports' forwards, where Roachock stopped the attack, but two brilliant marks by Webb and C.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Fry gave the latter a chance, and he kicked right into goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Bertram, relieved, and Phillips from a free gave Charlie Fry an opportunity which he fully capitalised kicking Port's third goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Roachock stopped another attack, and then Rawson, Dixon, and Guster made a forward movement.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Through the instrumentality of Kenneth McKenzie the ball was taken down to the centre, and J.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Ports, however, made a determined rush.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] McKenzie gave Phillips a long shot, and he hit the post.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] At quarter-time the board showed scores were level.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Ports with the aid of the wind started the second quarter with the first attack.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] However Jackson warded off the Ports rebounding to Shaw and Roberts who troubled the Ports' back line.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Woods subsequently receiving a free on the boundary from a very difficult angle successfully kicked the Norwoods' fourth goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] On kicking off a very bad attempt at marking by the Norwoods let in Gardiner, and he sent the ball forward.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Combe and Daly kept the Norwood goal out of danger on their end, and then the Ports tried the other wing, and worked the ball across to the pavilion, where Stephens, who was working very hard in the ruck, showed up.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] After the sphere had traversed the ground Hills tried a shot, and the ball passed just outside the post.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Kempster, beating two Norwoods, kept the play in the Norwoods' territory but an exchange of marks sent to the other end, where McGaffin and C.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Then for a time the Norwood back men were kept hard at work at the river end.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Eventually Phillips was given an opportunity but he could only manage another behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Norwood with a fast rush transferred play to the other end, but equally as fast was returned.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Bushby, Stephens, and Correll to futile shots.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] At half time Norwood held a one-goal lead.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] After the half time interval the Ports were the first to gain ascendency of the play with some aggressive tactics.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Fry gave John McKenzie a shot, which he missed.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Arthur Jackson worked the ball out of the Norwood defence, but the Ports were making a great effort in keeping the Norwood goal in danger.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] McKenzie would both miss chances, with the latter getting a behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Daly was instrumental in stifling the Port attack.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Again the Ports put all their power into the play, and Gardner finished up a nice run with a good kick.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Hills placed in front to Le Leu who finally converted an opportunity for Port and a loud cheer from their supporters announced that the scores were equal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Ports continued their ascendancy in the play for a short while but state of the scoreboard eventually forced the Norwood's into action and by a series of long kicks and marks they forced the Ports to defend.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Dixon placed up, and Shaw smartly passed to Guster, who proved reliable kicking the Norwood's fifth goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] A determined effort by the Ports placed the Norwoods' backs in trouble, and another behind came from Hamilton.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Gardner and Tomlin pressured any forward movements of the Norwood players keeping the ball in their opponents' territory.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] This eventually resulted in Davis putting Phillips in possession, but once more the usually accurate kicker sent the ball behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Woods raised the siege along the gate wing, and Daly securing tried a sixty-yard kick which was very close to registering a goal but only resulted in Norwood's second behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Rawson and Wilson kept the ball close up to the Port Adelaide goal with Kenneth McKenzie working hard to prevent a Norwood score.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] When Alfred Robert gained a chance at scoring an easy goal he mulled the opportunity and only registered a behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Bushby beat Daly, and the leather went to the other end, Phillips securing yet another behind for the Ports.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] When the final change took place the score was:— Norwood 5 goals 3 behinds to Port 4 goals 7 behinds.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] With deafening cries from the partisan supporters of both teams, the players took to the field and went into work at a great pace.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Norwoods had evidently reserved themselves for a big final stanza.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] A series of marks by Rawson, Daly, and McGrath gave Shaw an opportunity, and the game looked all over as the ball went right up to the goal, but it fell short, and J.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Taking it around the gate wing the Ports called upon the Norwoods to defend.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Hamilton dispatched to Hills, who kicked a behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Shortly after John McKenzie kicked Port Adelaide's ninth behind.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Norwoods played wonderfully well together, successfully executing long kicks and marks.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] They transferred the play to the Ports' end, where Webb defended.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Sending it along the pavilion wing Hills gave Phillips another chance, and he made amends for previous misses by equalizing the score.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] With time rapidly drawing on the teams were urged on by their supporters, and the Norwoods made a gallant effort, whilst the Ports defended in equal style.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The Norwood's however, seemed to have a little bit in hand, and by some good marking Waldron forwarded to McGaffin, and his kick put the Norwoods a goal ahead.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Hamilton seized up with the cramp and struggled to contribute for the rest of the game.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Resuming, the Norwoods again attacked, and their combined play was too good for their opponents.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] In a scrimmage some distance from the goal C.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Woods put his foot to the sphere and sent it between the uprights.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The umpire thinking a Port man had kicked it did not give a decision, and nothing was registered.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] By Mr Traits order the ball was kicked off from behind, and then some hot play ensued in the Ports' quarters.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] McKenzie got away from two Norwoods, but Roachock outwitted him.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Rawson, Roberts, and Gaster kept the ball forward, and Daly missed a running shot.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Bertram also tried a running shot, and a loud cheer greeted another Norwood goal.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] With everything to gain the Ports started off again, but before anything serious had eventuated the bell rang out, and the great contest was over, leaving the Norwood team premiers of 1889.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] The final score was Norwood—7 goals 4 behinds.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] From their previous match Norwood replaced Haldane, Honner and McCarthy with John McGrath, Oswald Bertram and Patrick Roachock.
[src:grand-final/1889-safa-grand-final] Port Adelaide replaced Miller with Maurice Lowe.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The **1896 VFA season** was the 20th season of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The season began on 2 May and concluded with a playoff match on 3 October, in which Collingwood defeated South Melbourne by one goal to claim its first and only VFA premiership.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] It was the final season in which the VFA was strongest senior competition in Victoria, with eight of its strongest clubs leaving the Association and establishing the rival Victorian Football League from 1897.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] In 1896, the VFA competition consisted of thirteen teams of 20 on-the-field players each.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Because there was an odd number of teams, at least one team had a bye each week; the idle club often travelled to Ballarat to play one of the local senior clubs in a non-premiership match.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] When reporting match scores in 1896, the number of goals and behinds scored by each team is given; however, only the number of goals scored is considered when determining the result of a match.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] This was the final VFA season before the introduction of the modern system of scoring, in which six points is awarded for a goal and one point is awarded for a behind.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The Association had no formal tie-breakers in cases where clubs were equal on premiership points.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Collingwood and South Melbourne finished level on 58 premiership points at the conclusion of the premiership matches, meaning a playoff match for the premiership was required between them.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Additionally, the clubs' for-and-against records were not quite identical: Collingwood had scored one goal more than South Melbourne for the season, but the fact that the tallies were so close helped to perpetuate the myth.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The fact that a playoff would be required between Collingwood and South Melbourne was known after Round 19: both Collingwood and South Melbourne had a bye in Round 20 with third-placed Essendon six premiership points adrift, leaving them with no chance of tying for or finishing first.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] As a result, the two clubs organised to stage their playoff match on Saturday 26 September, the same day as the other Round 20 matches, at the neutral East Melbourne Cricket Ground; arrangements were made and advertisements were published.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] However, on the Tuesday, delegates from all Association clubs voted 11–8 in favour of postponing the playoff match to Saturday 3 October, the following weekend.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] A second meeting was held on the Wednesday night after Collingwood and South Melbourne objected to the postponement, but the Association delegates again voted in favour of postponing the match, albeit by a reduced majority of 10–9.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] While Collingwood and South Melbourne initially discussed playing the match on 26 September anyway, in spite of the Association's decision, this proved to be unworkable as the Association declined to provide an umpire.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Subsequently, Collingwood arranged to play Bendigo Football League premiers Eaglehawk at Victoria Park during Round 20, winning 6.7 – 3.6, while South Melbourne used the week as a bye.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The playoff match itself was played at a high standard in front of 12,000 spectators at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Two late goals in the first quarter allowed Collingwood to open up a 4–2 lead at quarter time, but Collingwood went goalless through the second and third quarters as South Melbourne dominated the game and regained the lead at 5–4.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Collingwood tied the game early in the final quarter, then kicked the winning goal inside the final ten minutes to win 6–5.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] On the Saturday between Rounds 5 and 6, a Charity Cup event was held, the gate takings from which were donated to charity.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] The event consisted of four clubs – Collingwood, Essendon, Port Melbourne and South Melbourne – contesting a knock-out tournament of shortened matches at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on a single afternoon, a format which has since become known as a lightning premiership.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Each match was played over two periods of twenty minutes each.
[src:grand-final/1896-vfa-season] Both of these rule changes were soon adopted into all levels of the game.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] The **1954 NSWRFL season** was the forty-seventh season of the New South Wales Rugby Football League premiership competition, based in Sydney.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Ten rugby league football teams from across the city competed for the J.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Giltinan Shield during the season, which culminated in the first "mandatory" Grand Final played between South Sydney and Newtown.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] During the pre-season, Queensland and Australian international representative forward, Harold "Mick" Crocker signed a then record one-year deal for an Australian to move south and play for Sydney club Parramatta.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] 1954 marked the first season when a Grand Final was scheduled to determine the premiership winner.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Prior to that the season victors were either the minor premiers or decided by a final that followed two semi-finals.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] A Grand Final was only played if the minor-premier was defeated in a semi-final or final and exercised their right to challenge via a Grand Final.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Since 1954 a Grand Final has been played every year to determine the premiership winner.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] This season, in a New South Wales versus England match at the Sydney Cricket Ground, referee Aub Oxford watched in disbelief the players fighting around him like street-brawlers before turning his back and walking from the field.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Oxford never refereed again and the match remains the only top-level game ever abandoned in rugby league history.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] In 1954 South Sydney's Les Brennan set the standing record for the highest number of tries in a debut season with 29.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Newtown winger Ray Preston's 34 tries remains second only to Dave Brown's 38 in 1935 in the tally of tries scored in a season.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Preston and Kevin Considine combined for fifty-six tries during the season – easily a record for a pair of club wingers.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] In the last round on 21 August, Western Suburbs set a record for the highest losing score when they lost to Balmain 32–37.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] This was to be one of only two cases before the introduction of the 10-metre ruck rule in 1993 that a team scored over thirty points and lost the match.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] In spite of Newtown finishing as minor premiers they hadn't beaten South Sydney in either regular season encounter.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Souths had also won their semi-final meeting 24-14.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] In this, the NSWRFL's first Grand Final scheduled to determine the premiership winner, Souths were the victors.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Legendary fullback Clive Churchill was outstanding setting up three of his side's five tries.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] The Bluebags stayed in the contest through the kicking boot of their Test fullback Gordon "Punchy" Clifford.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] The following statistics are as of the conclusion of Round 18.
[src:grand-final/1954-nswrfl-season] Following the grand final, nine players from the NSWRFL were selected in a squad of eighteen to represent Australia in the 1954 Rugby League World Cup in France.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] The **2009–10 Celtic League** (known as the **2009–10 Magners League** for sponsorship reasons) was the ninth season of the league now known as Pro12 and the fourth with Magners as title sponsor.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] The season began in September 2009 and ended with the Grand Final on 29 May 2010.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] Ten teams played each other on a home-and-away basis, with teams earning four points for a win, two points for a draw and a bonus point for scoring four or more tries in a match.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] The losing team may also earn a bonus point if they lose by seven points or less.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] The ten teams competing consisted of the four Irish provinces, Munster, Leinster, Connacht and Ulster; two Scottish regions, Edinburgh Rugby and Glasgow Warriors; and four Welsh regions, Cardiff Blues, Newport Gwent Dragons, Ospreys and Scarlets.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] This season saw the introduction of a play-off structure similar to the English Premiership in order to determine the overall winner.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] The Ospreys won the final, defeating Leinster 17–12 in Dublin.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] Green background (rows 1 to 4) are play-off places.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] Note: Flags to the left of player names indicate national team as has been defined under IRB eligibility rules, or primary nationality for players who have not yet earned international senior caps.
[src:grand-final/2009-10-celtic-league] Players may hold one or more non-IRB nationalities.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The **2010–11 Magners League** was the tenth Celtic League season and the fifth with Magners as title sponsor.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The regular season began on 3 September 2010 and finished on the weekend of 6–8 May 2011.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] During these stages, each team played every other team both home and away and were awarded points according to the standard bonus point system.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] This was the second season to follow the play-off structure to determine the Magners League champion, with the top four teams qualifying for the semi-finals.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The winner of each semi final advanced to the Grand Final, which took place 28 May and was hosted by the team that finished highest in the table following the regular season.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The title was won by Munster who defeated Leinster by 19–9 at Thomond Park.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] This was the final season of the Celtic League sponsored by Magners.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The following season would see RaboDirect, the Irish subsidiary of Dutch financial company Rabobank, take over the sponsorship.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] At the same time, the league rebranded itself as Pro12.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] In May 2010, the Ospreys were fined £100,000 and docked 4 points from the 2010–11 season following their postponement of the away fixture at Ulster in the 2009–10 season.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] However, in September 2010, following an appeal by the Ospreys, the four point deduction for the 2010–11 season was overturned, although the £100,000 fine was upheld.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] Instead, the four point deduction was suspended for two years.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] A new broadcast deal saw games broadcast live on terrestrial television channels in Scotland and Ireland in addition to the established terrestrial coverage in Wales.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] The deal will be in place until the 2013–14 season.
[src:grand-final/2010-11-celtic-league] Note: Flags to the left of player names indicate national team as has been defined under IRB eligibility rules, or primary nationality for players who have not yet earned international caps.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The **2010 AFL Grand Final** was a series of two Australian rules football matches between the Collingwood Football Club and the St Kilda Football Club.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] They are considered the 114th and 115th grand finals of the Australian Football League (formerly the Victorian Football League),Note 1 and were staged to determine the premiers for the 2010 AFL season.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The premiership is usually decided by a single match; however, as the first grand final ended in a draw, a grand final replay was played the following week and was won by Collingwood.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Both grand finals were held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The first was held on 25 September 2010.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The game was attended by 100,016 spectators.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The match ended in a draw, with both teams scoring 68 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] This was the third draw for a grand final in the history of the VFL/AFL, with the previous two occurring in 1948 and 1977.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The premiership was decided by a full replay on 2 October 2010.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood defeated St Kilda by 56 points, marking Collingwood's fifteenth VFL/AFL premiership victory and their first since 1990.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was the last grand final to be replayed prior to the introduction of extra time.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood entered the 2010 season after having lost its preliminary final in 2009 against eventual premiers Geelong.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood was the best performed side of the home and away season, finishing with a record of 17–4–1 and winning its first minor premiership since 1977 and its first McClelland Trophy since 1970.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood progressed to the grand final after comfortable victories in the qualifying final against the Western Bulldogs by 62 points, and then against Geelong in the preliminary final by 41 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda entered the season after having won the 2009 minor premiership with the club's best ever home and away record of 20–2, but losing the grand final to Geelong by two goals.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] After winning the first four games of the season, the Saints hit a form slump coinciding with a serious hamstring injury to captain Nick Riewoldt.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] They would recover to win seven games in a row before Riewoldt's return, and finished third on the ladder with a record of 15–6–1.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] They overcame a heavily favoured Geelong team by four points in their qualifying final, and had a comfortable 24-point win over the Western Bulldogs in the preliminary final to advance to the grand final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was the first grand final between two Melbourne-based sides since the 2000 grand final.Note 2 Collingwood was the strong favourite to win, with major bookmakers offering around A$1.40 to A$1.45 for a Collingwood victory at the start of the game.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood and St Kilda met twice during the 2010 home-and-away season, each team winning once.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda won in round 3 at Etihad Stadium, 10.9 (69) to an inaccurate 4.17 (41), although Riewoldt was badly injured during the match.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In round 16 at the MCG, Collingwood was a comfortable winner over St Kilda by the score 15.10 (100) versus 6.16 (52).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The teams also met in the first round of the pre-season competition which St Kilda won by 1 point.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The first final marked the 41st time Collingwood had contested the VFL/AFL grand final, and the first time since the club lost back-to-back grand finals in 2002 and 2003.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The club was attempting to win its fifteenth VFL/AFL premiership, and its first since 1990.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was St Kilda's seventh grand final appearance, and its second in a row after the loss in 2009.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda was attempting to win its second premiership, the only previous premiership coming in 1966.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The matches were the second and third grand finals contested by the two clubs.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The only previous encounter was the 1966 grand final in which St Kilda won its only premiership, winning by a single point 10.14 (74) to 10.13 (73).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The 2010 decider was telecast nationwide by the Seven Network, on their main channel as well as the new high-definition (HD) digital channel 7mate.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The match was also broadcast for the first time in 3D.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Seven also televised the AFL grand final replay, on 2 October, albeit not in 3D nor in high-definition, as the equipment was being loaned in Sydney for the NRL Grand Final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The Seven Network also made use of the Skycam for the first time in an AFL grand final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The camera had previously been trialled by the Nine Network during its coverage of Friday Night Football in 2004, as well as the Rugby League State of Origin.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] According to *The Sydney Morning Herald*, 3.7 million people tuned into their TV to watch the drawn grand final, while a slightly smaller audience of 3.6 million tuned to watch the replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] However, 5.7 million witnessed the last 5 minutes of the replay, up from 5.6 million the previous week.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Aside from television, the grand final was also broadcast by a number of radio stations.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Due to Melbourne still being the heartland of Australian rules football, a higher number of radio stations broadcast locally into Melbourne, although almost all stations had their broadcast syndicated by regional stations nationwide.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Radio broadcasters included Triple M, SEN 1116, 3AW, 774 ABC Melbourne, 95.5 K-Rock, NIRS, FiveAA, 6PR and Crocmedia.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Prior to the match, entertainment was provided by INXS, who performed "Suicide Blonde", "New Sensation" and "Kick".
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] This was followed by the Melbourne Symphony Orchestra, who performed orchestral arrangements of the Collingwood and St Kilda theme songs.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Lyrics for the two songs were performed by Matt Hetherington (for Collingwood) and Paris Wells (for St Kilda).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] For the grand final replay, Lionel Richie was announced to perform the pre-match, as well as the post-match, entertainment.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Following Richie's performance, the team theme songs were performed as saxophone solos by Joe Camilleri (for Collingwood) and Wilbur Wilde (for St Kilda).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] For the replay, in place of the traditional around-the-ground parade of 2010 AFL retirees and medalists, famous members of the Collingwood and St Kilda football clubs were presented, including participants from the memorable 1966 VFL grand final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The match was played under dry conditions.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Rain was forecast towards the end of the match, but did not arrive until after the match had finished.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood scored the first goal only twenty seconds into the game, winning the first clearance and eventually getting the ball to Jolly to score from five metres out.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Stephen Milne scored St Kilda's opening goal in the 8th minute.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood then scored three goals in six minutes from Jarryd Blair, Alan Didak and Dale Thomas to open up a twenty-point lead.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] After the 17th minute, St Kilda was able to hold Collingwood scoreless, with goals to Riewoldt and Schneider bringing the margin back to six points at quarter time.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Generally, Collingwood had the better of the play early in the first quarter, attacking primarily through rebounds and turnovers.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda won the clearances 12–6 throughout the quarter, and it was through that clearance work that St Kilda was able to build their late-quarter recovery.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Lenny Hayes was instrumental in St Kilda's clearance work, acting as third-man-up in the ruck contests and collecting 10 disposals.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] All of the key statistics (contested possessions, inside-50s, tackles) except for clearances were fairly even through the quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood dominated the second quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] They won the clearances 16–6, and won the inside-50s 21–5, giving St Kilda almost no opportunity to score.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Overall, Collingwood managed 10 shots at goal, but took many from long distance, which affected their overall accuracy: their total score for the quarter was 3.6 (24) with one out on the full.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Goals were scored by Travis Cloke in the 3rd minute, Brent Macaffer in the 18th minute (from a holding the ball free kick against Robert Eddy and subsequent 50-metre penalty against Farren Ray) and Harry O'Brien in the 26th minute.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Of their remaining shots, three fell short and were touched or rushed for behinds, while Cloke missed two relatively easy shots—one from a 25-metre set shot directly in front and one from a snap shot 30 metres out—in the final two minutes of the quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] So dominant was Collingwood in the second quarter that St Kilda managed only two shots on goal, both set shots from outside 50 metres: one goal to Justin Koschitzke in the 12th minute, and one from Brett Peake in the 21st minute which fell short and was rebounded.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood entered half time with a 24-point lead.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Dane Swan was instrumental at stoppages in the second quarter, while Thomas and captain Nick Maxwell were both crucial at forcing rebounds.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda began to win clearances again, and after both teams mustered rushed behinds, Riewoldt scored the first goal of the quarter in the 5th minute from a coast-to-coast play.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Midway through the quarter, ruckman Michael Gardiner left the field injured, leaving St Kilda (who had omitted back-up ruckman Ben McEvoy for the game) without a recognised ruckman.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood had long-range shots at goal by Cloke and Chris Dawes fall short and rushed for behinds in the middle stages of the quarter, but could not score a goal.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The Saints kicked two goals in five minutes through Brendon Goddard and Sam Gilbert to close the gap to seven points in the 22nd minute.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Thomas had a good chance to score a goal late in the quarter, but missed with a wild snap shot under little pressure.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood took an eight-point lead into three-quarter time.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] After Collingwood's complete dominance of the second quarter, the third quarter was much more closely contested.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The teams were even in both clearances and contested disposals, and both managed six shots on goal.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In St Kilda's case, their six shots yielded 3.3 (21), while in Collingwood's case, they yielded only 0.5 (5)—including hitting the post once, two falling short and then getting touched through for behinds, and one falling short and being marked by an opponent for no score.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Hayes and Goddard were again prominent at the clearances, with both playing at various times as the third man up in ruck contests.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Part-time ruckman Jason Blake assumed much of the ruck responsibility following Gardiner's injury.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The final quarter was again a close contest.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Both teams had several inside-50s early in the quarter, but all were rebounded without score, with Maxwell and Goddard both prominent for their respective teams.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The first score of the quarter was not until the 9th minute, when Leon Davis crumbed a goal from a stoppage, extending the margin to 14 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the 12th minute, Eddy hit the post from a long tight set shot won after catching O'Brien holding the ball; the Saints then scored goals through Hayes in the 14th minute, and Milne in the 15th minute off the ensuing centre break to bring the margin back to one point.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the 19th minute, Riewoldt had a 45-metre snap shot at the goals from a stoppage which was bouncing towards the goals, but was touched on the line by a desperate dive from Maxwell, levelling the scores at 61 apiece.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Then, in the 20th minute, Goddard scored a goal from 20 metres out, directly in front, after taking a big specky over O'Brien.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] This gave St Kilda its first lead of the game, after Collingwood had been leading since the opening goal, 20 seconds into the game.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the 22nd minute, Cloke's attempt for goal was rushed behind after he was awarded a free kick.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the 26th minute, Maxwell created a turnover which resulted in a goal to Cloke from five metres, putting Collingwood back in front by a point.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood unsuccessfully attacked twice in the following two minutes from turnovers: a 50-metre set shot from Dawes which fell short and was punched out of bounds, and a 50-metre snap shot from Steele Sidebottom which fell short and was marked and rebounded.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The rebound from that mark ended with Hayes taking a long shot towards Milne from 60 metres, but the kick eluded Milne and bounced through for a behind, tying the game at 68-apiece in the 30th minute.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the final minute of the game, St Kilda had the ball in its forward line, and after fifteen seconds of scrambling around 15–25 metres from goal, Collingwood cleared to the boundary line on the wing.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Time elapsed, and the game finished drawn.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Lenny Hayes won the Norm Smith Medal for the drawn grand final comfortably, with 13 of a possible 15 votes, named best on ground by four of the five voters.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] He had 32 disposals, 12 tackles, five clearances, and five inside-50s.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Brendon Goddard placed second with seven votes, while Dale Thomas came third with six votes, receiving the most Norm Smith votes of any Collingwood player.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Sam Fisher and Nick Maxwell were the only other vote-getters with two votes each.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The final of the grand final sprint was held at half-time of the first final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was won by Luke Miles from St Kilda, with Tim Golds from Greater Western Sydney and Lewis Jetta from Sydney finishing second and third respectively.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The draw immediately sparked debate about the practice of staging a full-length replay instead of playing extra time.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Within a few days of the grand final, the organisers of several events already scheduled for 2 October made the commercial decision to reschedule their events to avoid a clash with the replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The inaugural A-League derby clash between cross-town teams the Melbourne Victory and new franchise Melbourne Heart was postponed for 8 October to maximise promotion and publicity opportunities.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The Victoria Racing Club moved the Turnbull Stakes to 3 October.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Cricket Victoria delayed the opening of the Victorian Premier Cricket season to the following weekend.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The Chris Mainwaring Legends Match, which raises money for Perth's Telethon, was moved to 9 October.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The scheduling of several AFL post-season events was also affected: Collingwood's Copeland Trophy presentation was rescheduled to December, and the start of trade week and the father–son bidding meeting were moved from 4 to 5 October (with trade week shortened by one day).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Many players had to reschedule their post-season holiday plans to be available to play in the replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In the grand final edition of the TV show *Before the Game*, Geelong's Harry Taylor predicted the draw and the subsequent Collingwood victory the next week.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] On Tuesday 28 September, the AFL announced a rule change such that any player who had played in the drawn grand final but missed the replay, through omission or injury, would still receive a premiership medallion if his team was victorious.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Under previous rules, players would not have received premiership medallions unless they were present in the team that won the premiership-deciding game.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] This would mean that Leon Davis, who would be replaced for the replay, would eventually receive a medallion (although he did not receive one during the match-day ceremony).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Another rule change, that if the replay was also drawn, extra time would be played instead of a second replay, was also rushed through.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Most of the game statistics were fairly even across the game.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Total disposals were won by St Kilda 338–326, contested possessions were won by Collingwood 153–148, and tackles were won by St Kilda 100–89.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The two most lopsided statistics were clearances, which St Kilda won 46–38, despite having ten fewer than Collingwood in the second quarter, and inside-50s, which Collingwood dominated 62–35.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Altogether, seven of Collingwood's 14 behinds were recorded as rushed, mostly from shots at goal which fell short and were touched or punched through.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The official crowd of 100,016 was the highest since the 1986 VFL grand final, exceeding the crowd of the 2008 AFL grand final by only four people.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The grand final replay was played on a day without cloud, with the temperature around 20 °C for most of the game.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood was still the strong favourite with bookmakers for the replay, although the odds had tightened since the drawn match: major bookmakers were offering odds of around $1.60 for a Collingwood win in the replay, compared with $1.40–$1.45 for the grand final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Prior to the first bounce, Nick Maxwell of Collingwood won the coin toss, and chose to kick to the (western) City End.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood almost scored the opening goal in the first minute of the game, but an off-the-ball free kick against Dane Swan stripped Travis Cloke of a set shot from the goal square.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The first score was registered in the 5th minute, a goal from a set shot by Tyson Goldsack.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Up until the 11th minute, Collingwood won the inside-50s 6–1.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Ben Johnson scored a goal for Collingwood in the 12th minute, and the Magpies led 14–0 after twenty minutes.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Brent Macaffer scored a crumbing goal for Collingwood from the goal square a minute later to extend the margin to 19 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Riewoldt would get one more chance to get a goal at the last minute, but his 45-metre kick missed to the left.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood led by 18 points at quarter time, and St Kilda was held goalless in the first quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda dominated in the first half of the second quarter, with a first score registered 33 seconds after the bounce.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Brendon Goddard finally scored St Kilda's first goal in the 15th minute from a 20-metre set shot.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] After missing two difficult shots at goal in the 17th and 18th minutes, Collingwood goaled twice in the space of one minute, through Macaffer and Darren Jolly.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The end of the quarter was filled with physical one-on-one contests with Collingwood willing to play for time, and no more goals were scored in the quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Two more opportunities for Collingwood ended up behinds but kept the pressure on St Kilda.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Finally, Adam Schneider had a set shot from 30m as the siren sounded, but only managed a behind.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] In general play, the second quarter was fairly even, with St Kilda winning the inside-50s 13–10, but while none of their missed opportunities were easy shots, the Saints' inability to convert the chances they had contributed to their increasing deficit.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood won the quarter 3.3 (21) to St Kilda's 1.6 (12) and took a 27-point lead into half time.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood dominated in the third quarter.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Following Schneider's minor score in the first 14 seconds of play, the Magpies responded with relentless pressure and strung together five straight scores, including a crumbing goal from Chris Dawes and consecutive goals by Sharrod Wellingham and Swan.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It took Justin Koschitzke to end that streak, after marking the ball from a Riewoldt kick from the centre square.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The two sides subsequently kicked goal for goal, with Didak, Lenny Hayes, Steele Sidebottom, and Sam Gilbert all registering goals.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda had four shots at goal for three goals, while Collingwood had eight for five goals, and a rushed behind.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood's three-quarter-time lead was 41 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Within two minutes, Dawes kicked a goal from about 40m out near the boundary line to stretch the margin to 47 points.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] From there, Collingwood's victory was never in doubt.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The two teams alternated goals throughout the final term.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Goals were scored by Dale Thomas (5th minute), Nick Dal Santo (7th minute), Harry O'Brien (12th minute, with the assistance of a 50-metre penalty), Stephen Milne (13th minute), Wellingham (17th minute), Milne again (25th minute), and finally Sidebottom (27th minute).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Kilda, Collingwood played out the final minute of the game running out the clock, and the ball was in the hands of Didak as the final siren sounded for Collingwood's 56-point victory.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Scott Pendlebury was awarded the Norm Smith Medal as the best player in the grand final replay, earning ten votes; he accumulated 29 disposals, seven marks and laid eleven tackles.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Steele Sidebottom (25 disposals, two goals) was a close second, with eight votes.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Thomas (27 disposals, eight marks) was third, with four votes.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Dane Swan (26 disposals, eleven tackles) was fourth with three votes, and Jolly, Luke Ball and Nathan Brown also polled votes.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The medal was fittingly presented to Pendlebury by former North Melbourne star Arnold Briedis, best on ground in the 1977 replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The statistics of the match, unlike the drawn grand final, were mostly dominated by Collingwood.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood beat St Kilda for disposals (379–326), kicks (250–178), marks (121–84) and tackles (87–67), while St Kilda had more handpasses than Collingwood (148–129).
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood was particularly dominant at ruck contests, winning 47 tap-outs to St Kilda's 26.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The win was the fifteenth VFL/AFL premiership won by Collingwood in its 114 years in the league.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was Collingwood's first premiership since 1990, only its second since 1958.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was the ninth time that Collingwood won both the premiership and the minor premiership in the same year, but the first time since 1930.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was also Collingwood's second consecutive premiership to be won in October and their first premiership since 1990.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] It was the third premiership won by Michael Malthouse as a coach, having previously won with the West Coast Eagles in 1992 and 1994, joining Leigh Matthews, David Parkin, Allan Jeans and Ron Barassi as coaches who have led more than one club to a premiership.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] With its loss, St Kilda became the first team since Collingwood in 2002 and 2003 to finish runners-up twice in a row.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The grand final replay was attended by 93,853 people, roughly 6,000 fewer than the drawn grand final.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] This was consistent with previous grand final replays in 1948 and 1977, both of which drew lower attendances than the drawn grand finals which preceded them.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] On Monday 4 October, the Match Review Panel charged St Kilda's Adam Schneider with striking Brent Macaffer in the third quarter of the replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Schneider was offered a two-week suspension for the incident.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] On Monday 13 December, the AFL commission discussed the possibility of introducing extra time to decide future drawn grand finals, but ultimately decided to retain the full grand final replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The provision for a grand final replay was eventually removed, and replaced with extra time, starting from the 2016 season, making 2010's game the last grand final replay in the league's history.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Tyson Goldsack's mother placed a successful bet on her son, who is usually a defender but started in the forward-line, to kick the first goal of the replay.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] *The Footy Show* host James Brayshaw drew attention to this in July 2011, amidst investigations into that season's controversial betting plunges on the defenders to kick the first goal, but the AFL cleared Goldsack and his mother of any wrongdoing.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] When named on Thursday night before the first final, St Kilda recalled Steven Baker who had not played since Round 13, due to a 9-game suspension, omitting Ben McEvoy.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood made two changes to their preliminary final team, bringing in Leon Davis and Simon Prestigiacomo and omitting Tyson Goldsack and Nathan Brown.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] However, prior to the start of the first final, Brown replaced Prestigiacomo, who withdrew due to a groin strain.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] The teams for the replayed grand final were announced on 30 September, with both sides making one change.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] Collingwood omitted out-of-form Leon Davis, who was replaced by defender Tyson Goldsack.
[src:grand-final/2010-afl-grand-final] St Kilda brought Ben McEvoy into the team, to replace injured ruckman Michael Gardiner.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Primarily in Australian sports, a **grand final** is a game that decides a sports league's premiership (or championship) winning team, i.e. the conclusive game of a finals (or play-off) series.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Synonymous with a championship game in North American sports, grand finals have become a significant part of Australian culture.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The earliest leagues to feature a grand final were in Australian rules football, followed soon after by rugby league.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Currently the largest grand finals are in the Australian Football League (AFL) and National Rugby League (NRL).
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Their popularity influenced other competitions such as soccer's A-League Men and A-League Women, the National Basketball League, Super Netball and European rugby league's Super League to adopt grand finals as well.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Most grand finals involve a prestigious award for the player voted best on field.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The Anglo-Norman term "grand" to describe a sporting event, documented in England as "grand match" in 1836, was used in Australia from the 1850s.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] A steeplechase in England has been called the "Grand National Steeple Chase" ("Grand National" alone for short) since at least 1839.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Use of the term in Australian Football dates back to the first organised and widely publicised match between Melbourne Grammar School and Scotch College on 7 August 1858 at Yarra Park (formerly Richmond Park).
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The game was advertised as the "grand football match" in the Melbourne Morning Herald and several other local newspapers.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1859, a "grand football match" was advertised in Richmond, Tasmania for St Patrick's Day on Friday 18 March.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In *The Argus* of 1861, the Royal Caledonian Society of Melbourne invited clubs to compete in a "grand football-match" which was to be football's first ever trophy, the Caledonian Challenge Cup, however the match did not proceed until the following year.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The earliest known event described as "grand" in Sydney was a cricket match in 1862.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In the 1871 South Yarra Challenge Cup, Carlton and Melbourne drew their three matches, but both clubs had won their remaining matches against the other clubs, Albert Park and South Yarra, meaning the Challenge Cup's only tiebreaker, head-to-head record, was unable to separate them.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Initially, a football premiership final appeared to be called a "grand final" only when the losers of a final were the minor premiers and they exercised the "right to challenge" the winners to a second premiership decider.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In the Victorian Football Association, which was Victoria's top level of senior football from 1877 until 1896, the premiership was typically awarded solely on the basis of the rostered premiership matches (known today as the home-and-away season).
[src:grand-final/grand-final] However, the VFA's rules stipulated that where two or more teams finished equal on premiership points, a playoff match or matches would be scheduled amongst those teams to decide the premiership.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] This was required in 1896, when South Melbourne and Collingwood finished level on top of the ladder with records of 14 wins and one draw.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The playoff match between them, which is retrospectively treated as Victoria's first Grand Final (it was actually the first match referred to as such), saw Collingwood defeat South Melbourne by 6.9 – 5.10 to win the club's first ever premiership.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] There had been one previous premiership playoff match during this time in the VFA, between Melbourne and Geelong in 1878, but this match did not break a tie for first place, as Geelong had a superior win–loss record to Melbourne: the match was organised to resolve a dispute between the two clubs.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Geelong defeated Melbourne by 5.12 – 1.4 to win the premiership.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1897, when eight teams broke away from the VFA to form the VFL, the concept of finals football was high on the agenda, with teams buoyed by the success and attendance from the 1896 Grand Final.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Over the following ten years, all top-level Australian football leagues adopted a finals structure.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1931, the VFL adopted a system, the Page–McIntyre system, which ensured a Grand Final, and the concept became entrenched.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Prior to 1889, the South Australian Football Association (SAFA, now SANFL) premiership was awarded to the team that finished top of the end-of-season ladder placings.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1889, Norwood and Port Adelaide finished equal first with 14 wins and one draw, meaning a play-off was required to determine the premiership.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In promoting the play-off, the local press referred to it as a "premiership match".
[src:grand-final/grand-final] This was played on October 5, and Norwood won the match 7.4 to 5.9.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1894, Norwood and South Adelaide finished with a 13–5 record from their 18 matches.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The play-off match was fixed for October 6, and despite a provision for 20 minute periods of extra time in the event of a draw at full time, the match was abandoned due to darkness with the scores level at 4.8 apiece.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The SAFA fixed a replay for October 10, Labor Day: this was the first of seven grand final replays in elite Australian football history.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Norwood won the replay 4.7 to South Adelaide 3.5, with Anthony "Bos" Daly kicking the winning goal as the final bell rang.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The New South Wales Rugby Football League (NSWRFL) experimented with a finals system in 1908, its inaugural year, but abandoned it the following season.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Finals were reintroduced in 1926, and the premiership decider appeared to only be called a "grand final" if it involved the minor premiers.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] By the 1930s, the NSWRFL adopted the term "grand final" to describe the premiership decider.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Up until 1954 a 'grand final' match was only held if the minor premiers were beaten.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The adoption of the VFL's Page–McIntyre system for the 1954 NSWRFL season meant for the first time grand finals would become necessary every season, so the term grand final has become used to describe all premiership deciders.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The tradition is maintained by the present-day NRL National Rugby League.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The term "Grand Final" was introduced to Europe in 1995 in a completely different sport—golf.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In that year, the Challenge Tour, the official developmental tour for the European Tour, launched its season-ending Challenge Tour Grand Final.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] British rugby league would adopt the term in 1998, two years after the start of Super League.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The Super League Grand Final has now become an accepted part of the British scene, and the term 'grand final' is used to describe the final of leagues below Super League as well, such as the Championship, Championship 1 and the Conference.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Prior to this, a *Championship Final* was introduced to determine the winner of the British Rugby Football League Championship in 1904, though it only became a regular fixture from 1906 onwards.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In 1973, the competition format was changed so that the championship was won by the team finishing top of the league table, with an end of season knock-out competition for the top teams that became known as the *Premiership* being created.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Starting in 2009–10, the rugby union competition historically known as the Celtic League, at the time involving teams from Ireland, Scotland and Wales, introduced a playoff system to determine its champion.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] (Although the league conducted a knockout competition in its early years, it was a parallel cup competition instead of a championship tournament.) The final match was branded as a grand final.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] This usage continued for the 2010–11 season, the first that included teams from Italy.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Starting with the 2011–12 season, the league's first as Pro12, the "Grand Final" terminology was scrapped; the final match of the competition now known as the United Rugby Championship is simply called the "Final".
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In the Philippines, the term "**grand finals**" (pluralized) usually refer to a final of TV series competition.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Notable series that had a "grand finals" are *The Voice of the Philippines* and *Idol Philippines*.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] It was used as early as 1994 for the *Battle of the Brains* quiz show.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The Grand Finals are also adopted in numerous reality television and even game shows.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In reality television, a number of selected finalists after surviving a pre-determined number of elimination rounds moved on to compete in the finals.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] In game shows, notably *Jeopardy!* (such as *Tournament of Champions* and *The Greatest of All Time*), these finalists compete in a two-legged round, based on the combined scores from both games, to determine the winner.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] A grand final replay is a method of deciding the winner of a competition when a grand final is drawn by replaying the entire match the following week, rather than playing overtime or extra time on the same day.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] It is commonly used in Australian rules football and most notably in the Australian Football League, where it was used three times, the last occasion being in 2010.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The AFL decided in 2016 that grand final replays would be abolished being replaced with extra time: no grand final has required extra time as of 2025.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Most sports leagues in Australia have a grand final breakfast to mark the beginning to grand final day.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] It is a social highlight on the Australian sporting calendar.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] Watching the event is a ritual for many footy fans and the function plays a huge role in the pre-match build-up for the grand final.
[src:grand-final/grand-final] The North Melbourne Football Club host the North Melbourne Grand Final Breakfast, while the National Rugby League typically host the NRL Grand Final Breakfast at Sydney Convention and Exhibition Centre in Darling Harbour.
